WEBVTT

00:00.734 --> 00:02.503
Narrator:
Tonight on "Shark Tank"...

00:02.503 --> 00:03.837
Hey, Sharks, we're here
to solve a big problem.

00:06.106 --> 00:07.975
Today,
we're fishing for Sharks.

00:07.975 --> 00:08.976
I knew it!

00:08.976 --> 00:10.444
I don't like
your approach.

00:10.444 --> 00:11.845
This isn't
the direction.

00:11.845 --> 00:13.480
Cut the throat, man.

00:13.480 --> 00:15.782
For me, there's a huge elephant
in the room.

00:15.782 --> 00:17.718
Are you losing money?
Yeah.

00:17.718 --> 00:20.020
How much?
Depending on the month,
somewhere between 40K and 50K.

00:20.020 --> 00:21.788
What?!
What a head-squeezer.

00:21.788 --> 00:23.056
This story's getting
better and better.

00:30.564 --> 00:32.299
Narrator: First in the Tank

00:32.299 --> 00:36.036
is a cosmetic company
for an underserved market.

00:45.546 --> 00:47.147
Hey, Sharks.
I'm Jon.

00:47.147 --> 00:48.315
And I'm Devir.

00:48.315 --> 00:51.084
We're from New York,
and we're seeking $600,000

00:51.084 --> 00:53.520
in exchange
for 5% of our company, Stryx.

00:53.520 --> 00:54.588
Oh, God.

00:54.588 --> 00:56.123
Do you know
what everybody in this room

00:56.123 --> 00:57.591
has in common
right now,

00:57.591 --> 00:59.626
besides
being on television?

00:59.626 --> 01:01.328
We're all
wearing makeup.

01:01.328 --> 01:02.896
But chances are,
the women are fine

01:02.896 --> 01:04.398
applying
and wearing makeup,

01:04.398 --> 01:06.533
but most men aren't nearly
comfortable enough

01:06.533 --> 01:07.868
to admit or use it.

01:07.868 --> 01:09.303
Sharks,
this happened to me

01:09.303 --> 01:10.637
on the day
of my wedding.

01:10.637 --> 01:13.740
The greatest day of my life,
and I woke up with a zit.

01:13.740 --> 01:14.741
And not just
any zit.

01:14.741 --> 01:16.343
As you can see...

01:16.343 --> 01:18.579
Ew.
...I mean, this thing was
the mother of all zits, okay?

01:18.579 --> 01:20.013
It was a volcano.

01:20.013 --> 01:22.149
It was just waiting
to erupt. Yuck.

01:22.149 --> 01:24.751
And while there were makeup
artists there at the wedding,

01:24.751 --> 01:26.720
I was too embarrassed
to do anything about it,

01:26.720 --> 01:28.589
and so my blemishes
were there to stay

01:28.589 --> 01:31.224
for the thousands of photos
that were taken that day.

01:31.224 --> 01:33.060
Every guy has an experience
like this,

01:33.060 --> 01:34.494
whether
it's a first date,

01:34.494 --> 01:36.697
an important pitch
like here on "Shark Tank,"

01:36.697 --> 01:38.265
or just
coffee with a friend.

01:38.265 --> 01:40.233
When you look your best,
you feel your best,

01:40.233 --> 01:42.202
which is why Stryx
is changing the way

01:42.202 --> 01:44.771
that men can instantly
fix their appearance with,

01:44.771 --> 01:46.807
you guessed it,
it's makeup for men.

01:46.807 --> 01:48.742
Stryx is
the first company ever

01:48.742 --> 01:51.244
to engineer cosmetic
and skincare products

01:51.244 --> 01:53.380
with completely
custom formulations

01:53.380 --> 01:55.382
and packaging
geared towards men.

01:55.382 --> 01:57.417
We launched
with a sleek, discreet,

01:57.417 --> 01:59.119
and very sexy
concealer tool

01:59.119 --> 02:00.287
and a tinted moisturizer,

02:00.287 --> 02:02.522
and since then,
we've launched seven products

02:02.522 --> 02:05.359
at the intersection
of cosmetics and skincare

02:05.359 --> 02:07.361
so that you can instantly
fix your appearance,

02:07.361 --> 02:09.496
including our
energizing eye tool

02:09.496 --> 02:11.732
and our beard
and brow gel comb.

02:11.732 --> 02:13.634
So, Sharks,
who's ready to join us

02:13.634 --> 02:15.035
and show the world...

02:15.035 --> 02:16.703
Both: There's nothing wrong
with handsome.

02:17.838 --> 02:19.840
So we don't have pens
in front of you.

02:19.840 --> 02:21.174
It's actually
our concealer tool,

02:21.174 --> 02:22.676
so if you
take a look there.

02:22.676 --> 02:25.012
So we have it designed
as a pen

02:25.012 --> 02:26.380
so that it's sleek
and discreet.

02:26.380 --> 02:27.547
O'Leary: So this is just
a concealer?

02:27.547 --> 02:28.615
Correct.

02:28.615 --> 02:30.150
Cuban: So let me start
at the beginning.

02:30.150 --> 02:33.020
What does concealer do, and what
are you supposed to do with it?

02:33.020 --> 02:34.721
So the formulation
is made

02:34.721 --> 02:36.023
so that if you want
to cover up a pimple,

02:36.023 --> 02:37.591
if you want to cover up
dark under-eye circles,

02:37.591 --> 02:38.925
you just dab it on
and you're done,

02:38.925 --> 02:42.029
so you don't need a primer,
a foundation, a sponge,

02:42.029 --> 02:43.397
a brush,
a setting powder.

02:43.397 --> 02:45.132
It's made to be
as easy as possible

02:45.132 --> 02:46.933
for guys
to cover up any problems.

02:46.933 --> 02:48.769
And with the concealer tool,
we found out

02:48.769 --> 02:51.238
one of the best uses for it
that guys were using it for

02:51.238 --> 02:53.740
is for dark under-eye circles,
like under-eye bags. Right.

02:53.740 --> 02:56.677
And so that's what led us to
launch the energizing eye tool,

02:56.677 --> 02:58.045
which is also
in front of you.

02:58.045 --> 02:59.479
It tightens the skin
underneath the eye,

02:59.479 --> 03:01.815
so it's meant to reduce
fine lines, wrinkles,

03:01.815 --> 03:03.450
and it's really
an anti-aging type of product.

03:03.450 --> 03:05.519
But how are you supposed to
even know how to do it?

03:05.519 --> 03:08.021
Like, to me,
it's like war paint, you know?

03:08.021 --> 03:10.490
You just, like, see a streak.
I mean, now what?

03:10.490 --> 03:11.858
That looks good.
Greiner:
Mark, really?

03:11.858 --> 03:14.161
So that's a huge thing
that we need to work on

03:14.161 --> 03:15.529
as part
of this brand,

03:15.529 --> 03:17.064
is education
around these products.

03:17.064 --> 03:18.432
Herjavec:
Good job, Mark.

03:18.432 --> 03:20.767
I actually use a product
like this all the time.

03:20.767 --> 03:22.135
Of course you do.

03:22.135 --> 03:24.037
I don't sleep enough,
so I get really baggy eyes.

03:24.037 --> 03:27.541
There's lots of products --
eye creams, everything --

03:27.541 --> 03:28.909
that are made for men.

03:28.909 --> 03:31.044
Correct.
You're saying
you're a brand-new category.

03:31.044 --> 03:32.446
What's the brand-new category?

03:32.446 --> 03:34.514
Nobody's approached
the cosmetic category

03:34.514 --> 03:35.615
from this angle.

03:35.615 --> 03:37.350
Like, for me,
when I was younger,

03:37.350 --> 03:39.186
I was bullied
out of my middle school

03:39.186 --> 03:40.721
because I put gel
in my hair,

03:40.721 --> 03:43.790
and that hit my confidence
for years.

03:43.790 --> 03:46.126
People bullied you because
you put gel in your hair?

03:46.126 --> 03:47.294
Yeah. Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
I had the same thing.

03:47.294 --> 03:48.462
This was also,
I mean --
Seriously?

03:48.462 --> 03:49.996
John: I would love to hear,
though, why this.

03:49.996 --> 03:51.465
I mean,
were you guys chemists?

03:51.465 --> 03:53.200
Were you guys
in this industry at all?

03:53.200 --> 03:54.835
So, no.
So when we first started,

03:54.835 --> 03:57.537
I partnered with
two professional makeup artists.

03:57.537 --> 03:59.372
They helped us
really be able to formulate

03:59.372 --> 04:01.241
the first-ever really
cosmetic products

04:01.241 --> 04:02.943
for men's skin
as opposed to women,

04:02.943 --> 04:04.845
so what had happened was
is I raised

04:04.845 --> 04:06.613
half a million dollars
to start.

04:06.613 --> 04:08.148
You what?
That was
before I raised

04:08.148 --> 04:10.217
half a million dollars
to launch the company. Wow.

04:10.217 --> 04:11.351
Who did you
raise it from?

04:11.351 --> 04:13.720
Friends, family,
and then connections.

04:13.720 --> 04:15.021
You got some
really good friends.

04:15.021 --> 04:16.289
O'Leary: What portion of
the company did you give away

04:16.289 --> 04:17.357
for the $500,000?

04:17.357 --> 04:20.827
So at the time,
we raised at about,

04:20.827 --> 04:23.296
you know,
a $1.5 million valuation.

04:23.296 --> 04:24.564
How long ago was that?

04:24.564 --> 04:26.700
That was
back in 2018. Okay.

04:26.700 --> 04:28.335
And now you're
at a $12 million valuation

04:28.335 --> 04:30.203
because you have amazing sales.
What are they?
Yes.

04:30.203 --> 04:34.107
So this year, we're at about
$130,000 in sales.

04:34.107 --> 04:35.609
That's it?

04:35.609 --> 04:36.610
Per month.
Per month.

04:36.610 --> 04:37.711
- Per month.
- Per month.

04:37.711 --> 04:39.146
I knew it!

04:39.146 --> 04:40.647
Greiner:
What's lifetime sales?

04:40.647 --> 04:42.182
About $2 million.

04:42.182 --> 04:43.316
$2 million? Okay.
Yes.

04:43.316 --> 04:46.119
How are you selling
$130,000 a month?

04:46.119 --> 04:49.623
Well, a big one is D2C,
ecom, retail, our own site.

04:49.623 --> 04:51.892
So we're about 95% D2C,

04:51.892 --> 04:55.395
and then last year,
we launched in CVS nationwide.

04:55.395 --> 04:57.264
We're the first
men's cosmetic brand.

04:57.264 --> 04:58.732
I'm amazed you got to CVS.
Good for you.

04:58.732 --> 05:01.067
For us, like,
retail is really

05:01.067 --> 05:02.502
a validation point.

05:02.502 --> 05:04.638
In CVS, we actually sit
in the shave aisle.

05:04.638 --> 05:05.639
We're not
in a cosmetic aisle.

05:05.639 --> 05:07.073
We're not
in the women's aisle,

05:07.073 --> 05:08.675
so we wanted to show
these products --
Oh. Clever.

05:08.675 --> 05:09.709
Yeah --
Can be normalized.

05:09.709 --> 05:10.777
What do
you sell them for?

05:10.777 --> 05:12.145
What's your average
selling price?

05:12.145 --> 05:13.613
It's around $30.

05:13.613 --> 05:15.315
85% gross margins.

05:15.315 --> 05:16.616
So why the --
why the value--

05:16.616 --> 05:18.018
I mean,
'cause you do understand

05:18.018 --> 05:21.421
that there's probably a family
that risked it all

05:21.421 --> 05:22.989
and they just needed
a shot.

05:22.989 --> 05:25.492
And you know you took
that space from them.

05:25.492 --> 05:26.860
Daymond, that's not fair
to do that, right?

05:26.860 --> 05:28.929
Every entrepreneur
wants a shot, right?

05:28.929 --> 05:30.197
At $12 million valuation,
Mark?

05:30.197 --> 05:31.464
Yeah,
it doesn't --

05:31.464 --> 05:33.033
Look, if it's gonna be worth
$200 million in 3 days,

05:33.033 --> 05:34.000
then it's cheap, right?

05:34.000 --> 05:35.035
But let me
ask a different question.

05:35.035 --> 05:36.503
It may be worth crap
in two days.

05:36.503 --> 05:38.438
Yeah, well,
so is every company facing that.

05:38.438 --> 05:39.673
So let me
ask a question.

05:39.673 --> 05:41.107
Oh, you're gonna give them
a $12 million, Mark?

05:41.107 --> 05:42.509
So when you raised
that much money

05:42.509 --> 05:45.612
and give away basically 1/3 of
your company at that point --

05:45.612 --> 05:46.947
Sorry,
I didn't hear that, Mark.

05:46.947 --> 05:48.481
Are you saying when you raised
the half a million,

05:48.481 --> 05:49.649
you gave up 1/3?

05:49.649 --> 05:51.218
It was a little bit
less than that.

05:51.218 --> 05:52.786
We have raised more
since then, actually.

05:52.786 --> 05:54.454
Oh, that's what
I was getting to, right?

05:54.454 --> 05:56.223
So how much do you guys own
right now?

05:56.223 --> 05:57.357
Between the two of us,

05:57.357 --> 06:00.460
we own a little bit more
than 1/3 of the company.

06:00.460 --> 06:02.596
Okay, so that's why you need
such a high valuation.
Herjavec: Got it.

06:02.596 --> 06:04.798
Because if you're asking
for that much money...
Devir: Well --

06:04.798 --> 06:06.433
...that's the only way you're
gonna retain any equity.

06:06.433 --> 06:08.201
Oh, my God.
Herjavec:
And so the total raise

06:08.201 --> 06:10.537
from beginning
was how much?

06:10.537 --> 06:13.406
Historical, right around
$1.5 million total raised.

06:13.406 --> 06:14.908
Wow.
O'Leary: Okay,
and if you do this run rate

06:14.908 --> 06:16.209
right now
at $130,000 a month,

06:16.209 --> 06:19.512
that's about $1.5 million
in sales for this calendar year.

06:19.512 --> 06:20.614
How much you
gonna make off that?

06:20.614 --> 06:22.282
We are not
net profitable.

06:22.282 --> 06:23.483
Everything we're making

06:23.483 --> 06:25.518
is going right back
into marketing, growth.

06:25.518 --> 06:26.953
Are you losing money?

06:26.953 --> 06:28.388
Yeah.
How much?

06:28.388 --> 06:31.191
Uh, depending on the month,
somewhere between 40K and 50K.

06:31.191 --> 06:32.626
- Can we get back to the product?
- Okay, so let's ask why.

06:32.626 --> 06:34.194
Mark, this story's
getting better and better.

06:34.194 --> 06:36.529
So let's find out why, right?
Because the margins are huge.

06:36.529 --> 06:38.298
Yes, 85%.
So if you're burning

06:38.298 --> 06:41.468
that much cash,
you are spending it somewhere.

06:41.468 --> 06:42.469
Yeah. Yeah.

06:42.469 --> 06:43.470
Advertising or...

06:43.470 --> 06:45.372
Yep, it's marketing primarily,

06:45.372 --> 06:47.340
but we're expecting to see
5X to 6X return

06:47.340 --> 06:48.475
on the acquisition cost.

06:48.475 --> 06:49.643
Of course you are.

06:49.643 --> 06:51.845
Why did you guys
decide to go to retail?

06:51.845 --> 06:54.714
Because that takes
a lot more capital

06:54.714 --> 06:56.516
in order to drive
sell-through...
It's true.

06:56.516 --> 06:58.385
...whereas
direct to consumer,

06:58.385 --> 07:00.387
you can get a return on ad
spend and see it directly, so
why did you make that choice?

07:00.387 --> 07:02.489
Correct.
But I love
the retail strategy, Mark,

07:02.489 --> 07:04.624
because I wouldn't know
about the product,

07:04.624 --> 07:06.893
but if I go to a CVS
in the shaving aisle,

07:06.893 --> 07:08.228
I'm gonna see
the product. Yeah,
but that's so expensive.

07:08.228 --> 07:09.663
It's also
very validating.

07:09.663 --> 07:11.298
Our number-one competitor
is the stigma here,

07:11.298 --> 07:13.033
so for guys
to see these products

07:13.033 --> 07:15.602
right next to other
brands that they know and
love and have used --

07:15.602 --> 07:17.437
Yeah, but I'm not saying
that's wrong, right?

07:17.437 --> 07:18.805
But one
of the biggest things

07:18.805 --> 07:21.274
I try to teach my entrepreneurs
is conserve your cash.

07:21.274 --> 07:22.442
Yeah.

07:22.442 --> 07:24.544
Because stuff happens,
and so you're gonna

07:24.544 --> 07:27.314
have to raise
more than this $600,000, too.

07:27.314 --> 07:29.983
So now you guys are gonna
have to give away 10%,

07:29.983 --> 07:33.186
15%, 20% of your 33%,

07:33.186 --> 07:36.222
and then you guys are gonna
end up with nothing.

07:36.222 --> 07:38.391
For me, there's a huge elephant
in the room,

07:38.391 --> 07:40.026
and that is
that this packaging

07:40.026 --> 07:42.996
tells me nothing
about your product whatsoever.

07:42.996 --> 07:44.531
And Stryx, the name.

07:44.531 --> 07:47.334
I have no idea
it's makeup for men at all,

07:47.334 --> 07:50.503
so you could probably be selling
so much better

07:50.503 --> 07:52.772
if those things
were clear on here.

07:52.772 --> 07:55.909
And for those reasons,
I'm out.

07:55.909 --> 07:57.811
Thank you.
Thank you.

07:57.811 --> 07:59.479
The valuation's
a little high.

07:59.479 --> 08:01.915
I'd really rather
work with people

08:01.915 --> 08:03.283
who need it
a little bit more,

08:03.283 --> 08:06.252
not second raising
and all that kind of money.

08:06.252 --> 08:07.354
This is just not
a business for me.

08:07.354 --> 08:08.822
I'm out.

08:08.822 --> 08:10.323
Thank you.
Thank you.

08:10.323 --> 08:12.492
Cuban:
I love the category.

08:12.492 --> 08:16.029
I mean, I think it's been due
for a long, long time,

08:16.029 --> 08:17.731
but I don't like
your approach.

08:17.731 --> 08:21.434
You try to hide the fact
that it's makeup a little bit.

08:21.434 --> 08:23.703
I think you got to own it more
because that's the only way

08:23.703 --> 08:25.605
you're gonna change
hearts and minds.

08:25.605 --> 08:29.809
If you convince bro culture
to do it, you change everything.

08:29.809 --> 08:31.945
I would take
a completely different approach.

08:31.945 --> 08:33.646
You know,
you guys have made your choices,

08:33.646 --> 08:35.815
so for those reasons,
I'm out.

08:35.815 --> 08:37.350
Thank you. Thanks.

08:37.350 --> 08:38.518
I'm not gonna tell you
how to run your business.

08:38.518 --> 08:40.153
I expect you to do that
on your own.

08:40.153 --> 08:41.888
I'm just an investor.

08:41.888 --> 08:43.556
When I see a good idea,
I like it.

08:43.556 --> 08:45.025
I don't like
your valuation.

08:45.025 --> 08:46.426
I don't think you're worth
12 million bucks, okay?

08:46.426 --> 08:47.894
Sorry.
I just don't.

08:47.894 --> 08:49.362
Herjavec: Oh, I think there's
a royalty coming.

08:49.362 --> 08:50.597
Cuban:
Yeah, I think so, too.

08:50.597 --> 08:51.831
- Sounds like it, yeah.
- There may be.

08:51.831 --> 08:52.899
In fact, it's because
I understand your issue

08:52.899 --> 08:54.968
around your
capital needs.

08:54.968 --> 08:57.270
If you're getting into retail
with CVS and others,

08:57.270 --> 08:59.806
you're gonna get POs,
and it's tying up your capital.

08:59.806 --> 09:02.042
The more you grow,
the more capital is tied up,

09:02.042 --> 09:03.610
so the way I'm gonna
structure my offer

09:03.610 --> 09:06.780
is I'm gonna give you $300,000
as a factoring loan.

09:06.780 --> 09:09.616
36 months, 11 1/2%, okay?

09:09.616 --> 09:10.750
Oh.

09:10.750 --> 09:13.153
The other $300,000 is equity
for 2 1/2%,

09:13.153 --> 09:17.257
and I'm putting a royalty on it
on per package of 2 bucks

09:17.257 --> 09:20.326
until I get my $600,000 back
'cause you can afford it.

09:20.326 --> 09:23.696
And then it drops down
to 25 cents in perpetuity,

09:23.696 --> 09:25.999
which is nothing,
but I'm part of the game.

09:25.999 --> 09:27.934
Kevin,
I think you actually

09:27.934 --> 09:30.003
hit a new low
with this offer.

09:30.003 --> 09:32.005
Well, if you have something
better, Robert, feel free.

09:32.005 --> 09:33.506
Not only are you
being a loan shark,

09:33.506 --> 09:36.376
you're also adding
a royalty to it.

09:36.376 --> 09:37.977
Yeah.
I think this is
the first time.

09:37.977 --> 09:39.112
If you have --
<i>And</i> equity!

09:39.112 --> 09:40.313
Listen,
it's an offer.

09:40.313 --> 09:42.082
I don't hear any others.
What's your offer?

09:53.726 --> 09:55.795
Narrator:
Three Sharks are out.

09:55.795 --> 09:58.631
Jon and Devir have an offer
on the table from Kevin

09:58.631 --> 10:01.034
for their makeup brand
for men, Stryx,

10:01.034 --> 10:03.470
but Robert may also
be interested.

10:03.470 --> 10:05.638
Herjavec: Not only are you
being a loan shark,

10:05.638 --> 10:08.441
you're also adding
a royalty to it.

10:08.441 --> 10:09.843
Yeah.
I think this is
the first time.

10:09.843 --> 10:11.311
If you have --
<i>And</i> equity!

10:11.311 --> 10:13.513
What's your offer?

10:13.513 --> 10:16.349
Yeah, I think Kevin's
double dipping

10:16.349 --> 10:17.617
on his offer
with you guys.

