One of the worst jokes.

12:12.365 --> 12:14.467
Narrator: In Season 10,
Kelsey Moreira pitched

12:14.467 --> 12:16.536
her edible
cookie-dough company, Doughp,

12:16.536 --> 12:18.037
and left without a deal
from a Shark.

12:18.037 --> 12:19.572
It's not something

12:19.572 --> 12:21.374
that is a healthy enough
option for me.

12:21.374 --> 12:23.576
Let's see
what she's up to now.

12:23.576 --> 12:24.944
Moreira: It was pretty crushing
to leave

12:24.944 --> 12:27.213
without a deal that day,
but I did take away

12:27.213 --> 12:29.449
a little nugget of advice
from the Sharks.

12:29.449 --> 12:33.019
I made a portion-controlled
product called Doughp Drops.

12:33.019 --> 12:35.722
Doughp was created after
I made the amazing decision

12:35.722 --> 12:37.023
to get sober.

12:37.023 --> 12:39.692
I rediscovered my love of baking
and really who I was.

12:39.692 --> 12:41.461
I pitched to the Sharks
to open up

12:41.461 --> 12:43.529
a new brick-and-mortar store
in Las Vegas.

12:43.529 --> 12:45.064
Though I didn't get funding
in the Tank,

12:45.064 --> 12:46.666
I found some outside capital,

12:46.666 --> 12:48.568
and I was able
to open up that store.

12:48.568 --> 12:51.638
In 2019,
I did $1.2 million in sales.

12:51.638 --> 12:53.072
Then the pandemic hit,

12:53.072 --> 12:57.510
and if you fast-forward to 2020,
we did $2.7 million in sales.

12:57.510 --> 12:59.879
And $2.5 million of that
was online,

12:59.879 --> 13:01.447
so it made the most sense
to close

13:01.447 --> 13:04.150
our brick-and-mortar storefront
to focus entirely online,

13:04.150 --> 13:06.853
where our mission
can reach more people than ever.

13:06.853 --> 13:09.622
We just rolled out
at Costco and Walmart,

13:09.622 --> 13:12.725
and we are live at Harmons,
New Seasons, and Foxtrot.

13:12.725 --> 13:15.128
Edible dough,
and you can bake it.

13:15.128 --> 13:17.864
Moreira: We recently aired
on QVC, and it went so well

13:17.864 --> 13:19.465
that they're bringing us back
later this year

13:19.465 --> 13:20.867
to show off our Doughp Drops.

13:20.867 --> 13:21.934
You're going down
a wrong path.

13:21.934 --> 13:22.969
You go,
"You know what?

13:22.969 --> 13:24.504
I'm gonna return
to a passion of mine,

13:24.504 --> 13:25.672
which is baking."

13:25.672 --> 13:27.206
Way to go, woman.

13:27.206 --> 13:30.543
My sales when I pitched to
the Sharks was around $800,000.

13:30.543 --> 13:35.281
4 years later, our lifetime
sales are $9.4 million.

13:35.281 --> 13:39.052
Now I'm happily married, and I'm
going on seven years sober.

13:39.052 --> 13:41.554
And we started
the Doughp for Hope initiative.

13:41.554 --> 13:44.490
Doughp for Hope has donated
more than $60,000,

13:44.490 --> 13:46.492
working to break the stigma
around mental health

13:46.492 --> 13:48.661
and addiction recovery.

13:48.661 --> 13:50.663
I want to make sure that
if there's anybody out there

13:50.663 --> 13:52.465
who is struggling,
reach out for help.

13:52.465 --> 13:55.234
There is a lot of joy
waiting on the other side.

13:55.234 --> 13:57.970
What we're doing at
Doughp for Hope and the messages

13:57.970 --> 14:01.040
that I get from customers
are exactly what fuels me

14:01.040 --> 14:03.242
to fight another day
and reach more people

14:03.242 --> 14:06.145
and hope that we can change
more lives along the way.

14:17.190 --> 14:18.858
Narrator:
Next up is a product

14:18.858 --> 14:21.094
to make water sports
more comfortable.

14:29.769 --> 14:31.504
Hey, Sharks.
My name is Wes.

14:31.504 --> 14:32.538
And I'm Greg.

14:32.538 --> 14:34.273
We paddled up
the coast of California

14:34.273 --> 14:35.842
to see if you want
to take a bite

14:35.842 --> 14:37.543
out of our company...

14:37.543 --> 14:38.945
Both: Driftline.

14:38.945 --> 14:41.013
We're here today
seeking $100,000

14:41.013 --> 14:42.915
for 10% equity
in our company.

14:42.915 --> 14:45.918
Driftline is a revolutionary
water-sports apparel brand

14:45.918 --> 14:47.420
based out
of San Diego.

14:47.420 --> 14:49.555
We're here to solve
a big problem.

14:49.555 --> 14:51.224
See,
a couple of years ago

14:51.224 --> 14:53.025
during a dawn patrol
surf session,

14:53.025 --> 14:54.827
it was that transitional
time of year

14:54.827 --> 14:57.697
where the water was just
too warm for a full wetsuit

14:57.697 --> 14:59.599
and too cold for your
traditional board shorts.

14:59.599 --> 15:00.600
A net liner?

15:00.600 --> 15:02.168
Do people even still wear
these things?

15:02.168 --> 15:03.970
They're
insanely uncomfortable

15:03.970 --> 15:05.838
and don't provide
any warmth or protection.

15:05.838 --> 15:07.640
There has to be
a better way.

15:07.640 --> 15:09.742
And that's why
we created Drifties.

15:09.742 --> 15:12.412
Drifties are the premier
two-in-one board short

15:12.412 --> 15:14.514
with a patent-pending
wetsuit liner

15:14.514 --> 15:16.816
connected to a stylish
outer shell,

15:16.816 --> 15:19.719
offering comfort,
warmth, and chafe protection

15:19.719 --> 15:22.155
specifically designed
for water sports.

15:22.155 --> 15:24.157
And we've all seen
that guy at the beach

15:24.157 --> 15:25.358
doing the classic waddle

15:25.358 --> 15:27.627
to avoid the excruciating pain
of chafing,

15:27.627 --> 15:29.695
but with Drifties'
cloud-like wetsuit liner,

15:29.695 --> 15:30.930
we solved that problem

15:30.930 --> 15:32.999
while keeping you warm
and supported.

15:32.999 --> 15:34.167
Drifties have been tested

15:34.167 --> 15:36.202
by almost every
water-sport athlete out there.

15:36.202 --> 15:37.804
They've also been tested

15:37.804 --> 15:41.107
in the most extreme conditions
all over the globe.

15:41.107 --> 15:43.776
And remember, you never
want to swim with sharks...

15:43.776 --> 15:45.077
Both:
Without your Drifties.

15:45.077 --> 15:46.879
Good job, guys.

15:46.879 --> 15:48.948
So each of you has a pair
of Drifties in front of you.

15:48.948 --> 15:51.551
It feels like a neoprene.
Is it a neoprene?
That's what it is.

15:51.551 --> 15:54.587
Neoprene is a rubber foam
that basically stores heat

15:54.587 --> 15:56.255
and prevents
that initial cold shock

15:56.255 --> 15:58.724
that you see guys get when
they first step in the water.

15:58.724 --> 16:03.496
So basically, it's a wetsuit
married to board shorts.

16:03.496 --> 16:05.331
Correct.
We combined the two.

16:05.331 --> 16:06.899
Hadn't really been done before, actually.

16:06.899 --> 16:09.035
Yeah, we actually have applied
for our utility patent on it,

16:09.035 --> 16:10.336
and hopefully get it
in the next couple months.

16:10.336 --> 16:11.838
Good for you guys.
It seems
really smart to me.

16:11.838 --> 16:14.407
I mean, I will tell you,
it's really great quality.

16:14.407 --> 16:15.575
Tell us
about your sales.

16:15.575 --> 16:16.809
Currently,
year to date,

16:16.809 --> 16:19.378
we're actually
at about $125,000 in sales.

16:19.378 --> 16:21.714
Last year, we did
about $100,000 in sales,

16:21.714 --> 16:24.817
and we're projected on pace
to do about $200,000 this year.

16:24.817 --> 16:26.686
How are you selling these --
direct to consumer,

16:26.686 --> 16:28.888
do you put them
in specialty stores?

16:28.888 --> 16:31.624
So right now, we're actually
99% direct to consumer.

16:31.624 --> 16:34.360
Are you spending a lot of money
to get people to your site?

16:34.360 --> 16:35.561
Actually,
not really.

16:35.561 --> 16:37.363
This past year,
we only really spent

16:37.363 --> 16:38.998
about $10,000
in marketing.

16:38.998 --> 16:41.200
What does it cost?
Sorry, you never told us.

16:41.200 --> 16:43.135
So those retail
for $89.

16:43.135 --> 16:45.905
It costs $25 to make,
$33 landed.

16:45.905 --> 16:47.874
I'm surprised.
I mean, that's not bad at all.

16:47.874 --> 16:49.509
- Not bad at all.
- Because this is complicated.

16:49.509 --> 16:50.843
Yeah, well,
that's why we went through

16:50.843 --> 16:52.345
so many
different manufacturers

16:52.345 --> 16:54.680
and iterations to get the real
material and product we need.

16:54.680 --> 16:56.983
And is your history
in manufacturing?

16:56.983 --> 17:00.086
No, actually, I had
a sales marketing background.

17:00.086 --> 17:02.321
I actually was taking night
classes for graphic design,

17:02.321 --> 17:03.723
which is
my full-time now,

17:03.723 --> 17:05.825
and that's kind of
what spawned the idea.

17:05.825 --> 17:08.628
When we had that legitimate
lightbulb moment on the beach,

17:08.628 --> 17:11.063
I needed a project for school,
and I was like,

17:11.063 --> 17:13.065
"Well, let's just, you know,
see if I can brand this."

17:13.065 --> 17:14.267
That's great.
That's great.

17:14.267 --> 17:15.768
And by the end,
we actually had a business.

17:15.768 --> 17:17.470
And you did it.
What's your background?

17:17.470 --> 17:19.305
So I'm actually
a financial background,

17:19.305 --> 17:21.707
and now I'm more in tech
and marketing sales.

17:21.707 --> 17:24.310
Herjavec: It is
a fantastic idea.

17:24.310 --> 17:26.746
What I'm struggling
with is

17:26.746 --> 17:29.315
can you sell enough
just shorts

17:29.315 --> 17:32.151
to make
a sustainable business?

17:32.151 --> 17:33.786
That's part of
where we have this patent

17:33.786 --> 17:35.087
that we're
hopefully gonna get

17:35.087 --> 17:36.455
in the next
couple of months here,

17:36.455 --> 17:38.424
but really,
what we're building

17:38.424 --> 17:39.859
is not
just for surfing.

17:39.859 --> 17:42.194
We're also expanding
into water sports

17:42.194 --> 17:45.364
that need specific iterations
on the actual product

17:45.364 --> 17:46.999
specifically for
that sport.

17:46.999 --> 17:48.434
Give me an example
of that.
So, for instance,

17:48.434 --> 17:50.436
kayaking is different
from surfing,

17:50.436 --> 17:52.171
and you can add
additional lengths

17:52.171 --> 17:53.906
to the neoprene
and things like that.

17:53.906 --> 17:56.342
So you can iterate under
the umbrella of the patent

17:56.342 --> 17:58.377
specifically for
different water sports.

17:58.377 --> 18:00.179
How much money
will you guys make this year?

18:00.179 --> 18:01.781
We're pretty much
break even at this point

18:01.781 --> 18:03.950
'cause we're putting
everything back into R&D,

18:03.950 --> 18:05.518
and honestly,
right now,

18:05.518 --> 18:07.320
we have
that funnel of people

18:07.320 --> 18:08.754
that want
to buy our product.

18:08.754 --> 18:10.823
We just need to place
bigger purchase orders

18:10.823 --> 18:13.492
to drive down the cost
and increase the margins.

18:13.492 --> 18:15.161
Herjavec: Do you have
the orders,

18:15.161 --> 18:17.163
or do you think
you'll get orders

18:17.163 --> 18:18.698
if you drive down
the cost?

18:18.698 --> 18:21.200
So we've already sold out
of SKUs and styles

18:21.200 --> 18:22.802
for this
upcoming season,

18:22.802 --> 18:24.804
and the problem is
now people want them.

18:24.804 --> 18:26.339
So you cannot keep up
with the orders at the moment.

18:26.339 --> 18:27.373
No.

18:27.373 --> 18:29.075
It's a very good innovation.

18:29.075 --> 18:31.310
You know,
I look at million valuation.

18:31.310 --> 18:32.812
I don't think that's
that crazy,

18:32.812 --> 18:34.947
but I just don't know
how big this market is.

18:34.947 --> 18:36.482
That's the only reason
I'm out.

18:36.482 --> 18:40.252
I just don't feel
the scaling of it.

18:40.252 --> 18:42.488
This is not for me.
I'm out.

18:42.488 --> 18:47.994
This is a really phenomenal job
you've done in the creativity,

18:47.994 --> 18:49.729
putting
the two things together,

18:49.729 --> 18:51.530
but, you know,
I like to hit, like,

18:51.530 --> 18:52.932
a broad,
mass audience.

18:52.932 --> 18:56.569
Love it, love you,
but because it's niche, I'm out.

18:56.569 --> 18:59.338
I'm not sure about
the expansion,

18:59.338 --> 19:01.774
like you were saying,
how easy that's gonna be,

19:01.774 --> 19:04.310
but I do believe
that if you're in that world,

19:04.310 --> 19:05.711
you buy a pair,

19:05.711 --> 19:07.780
you're never gonna go back
to a regular... Right.

19:07.780 --> 19:09.181
...board short again,
right?

19:09.181 --> 19:11.784
But there's two other Sharks
here that are in the space.

19:11.784 --> 19:14.587
Mark, he's had rockstar numbers
with the paddleboard company,

19:14.587 --> 19:16.055
and, Robert,
you have --

19:16.055 --> 19:17.823
Hamboards, Sand Cloud,

19:17.823 --> 19:19.659
and Tipsy Elves
out of San Diego.

19:19.659 --> 19:20.993
I think you need
a collaboration

19:20.993 --> 19:23.029
with somebody who can
bring you other people,

19:23.029 --> 19:25.164
members and other people
marketing collectively.

19:25.164 --> 19:26.832
You don't compete.
You complement each other.

19:26.832 --> 19:28.467
So I don't think
I can add any value here.

19:28.467 --> 19:30.670
I'm out.
I appreciate it.

19:30.670 --> 19:32.138
Cuban: Hey, guys, congrats on
what you've accomplished.

19:32.138 --> 19:33.406
It's super smart.

19:33.406 --> 19:35.241
My problem is I don't know
if it can be big enough.

19:35.241 --> 19:37.910
You know, you can be a
$2 million, $3 million company,

19:37.910 --> 19:39.812
but it's really not
a fit for me.

19:39.812 --> 19:42.381
So for those reasons,
I'm out.

19:42.381 --> 19:45.017
Herjavec: Yeah, you know,
I'm definitely in this space,

19:45.017 --> 19:47.319
but it's got
to be enough...

19:47.319 --> 19:49.855
Yeah.
...that it's worth
my time.

19:49.855 --> 19:51.657
We know
this space well.

19:51.657 --> 19:53.759
We can really help you
with all that.

19:53.759 --> 19:56.362
I just can't do it
for 10%.

19:56.362 --> 19:58.864
What can you do it for,
Robert?

19:58.864 --> 20:01.067
I'll actually give you
a little more money.

20:01.067 --> 20:04.270
There's a term I love,
which is accelerate to fail,

20:04.270 --> 20:05.871
meaning I think
you got to go faster

20:05.871 --> 20:08.340
to find that breaking point
in the business.

20:08.340 --> 20:10.242
Yeah.
Let's not do this
for 10 years.

20:10.242 --> 20:12.044
Let's accelerate.

20:12.044 --> 20:13.479
I sense
an offer coming

20:13.479 --> 20:15.681
that's going to be
very painful.

20:15.681 --> 20:19.385
I'll give you a $150,000,
