20:19.385 --> 20:20.619
Ouch.

20:20.619 --> 20:22.154
I'm chafing.
I'm chafing.

20:22.154 --> 20:23.189
Oh.

20:25.558 --> 20:28.227
I mean, I -- we very much
appreciate that.

20:28.227 --> 20:31.831
Would you
bump that down to 15%?

20:31.831 --> 20:32.898
No.

20:32.898 --> 20:34.333
Okay.
No, no.

20:34.333 --> 20:36.535
There is only one Shark
that's in

20:36.535 --> 20:38.871
because I think I understand
the complexity

20:38.871 --> 20:40.239
and how hard this is. Yeah.

20:40.239 --> 20:43.008
If you get the patent --
if we get the patent --

20:43.008 --> 20:44.877
we're gonna
more than $150,000.

20:44.877 --> 20:46.679
It's a whole nother... Scale.

20:46.679 --> 20:48.547
Like at this point, though,

20:48.547 --> 20:52.084
a little more money,
let's go faster.

20:52.084 --> 20:53.919
Well, Greg and I --
I mean...

20:55.588 --> 20:57.423
You know, Wes,
I can't read lips,

20:57.423 --> 20:58.891
so you don't have to
cover your mouth.

20:58.891 --> 21:00.926
Yeah, that's fair.
That's fair.

21:00.926 --> 21:02.528
I mean,
we definitely,

21:02.528 --> 21:04.630
you know, love the work
that you've done in the space.

21:04.630 --> 21:07.500
I mean, would you do something
down to 20%?

21:07.500 --> 21:10.035
I mean, can we get you
to that number?
No, no.

21:10.035 --> 21:12.371
I just -- I know
how much work it is.

21:12.371 --> 21:13.906
I mean,
I think the highest

21:13.906 --> 21:15.508
we could probably go
is 25%.

21:17.076 --> 21:18.544
Robert,
that's reasonable.

21:18.544 --> 21:19.845
It is reasonable.

21:19.845 --> 21:22.181
I'm offering you more money.
Let's not forget that.

21:22.181 --> 21:24.116
And, you know, honestly,
if I'm worth 25%, I'm worth 33%.

21:24.116 --> 21:25.985
Cuban: That's a steal
for you, Robert.

21:25.985 --> 21:27.553
And that's what I felt
comfortable with.

21:27.553 --> 21:29.588
That's my gut feel.

21:29.588 --> 21:31.557
I'll give you $100,000
for 20%.

21:33.092 --> 21:34.593
Greiner: Wow.

21:34.593 --> 21:36.562
But you got
to take it right now.

21:36.562 --> 21:38.430
Say yes.

21:38.430 --> 21:41.100
I think the highest we can
go for that is 15%.

21:41.100 --> 21:43.936
Yeah, guys, I mean, think about
what's on the table right now.

21:43.936 --> 21:46.572
I offered you
$100,000 for 20%.

21:46.572 --> 21:48.974
You only have 5% flexibility,
and you said you need us.

21:48.974 --> 21:51.877
I mean, I guess you're
indecisive, so I'm out again.

21:53.779 --> 21:55.548
What are you gonna do,
Robert?

21:55.548 --> 21:57.616
I think if you're comfortable
at 25%,

21:57.616 --> 21:59.251
you're comfortable
at 28%.

21:59.251 --> 22:01.353
I'll come down
from 33% to 28%.

22:05.324 --> 22:08.093
What a head-squeezer.

22:08.093 --> 22:09.261
Yeah.

22:09.261 --> 22:12.031
I mean, we came here
kind of with numbers in mind,

22:12.031 --> 22:14.233
so unfortunately, we're gonna
have to pass at that number.

22:14.233 --> 22:16.001
You got to do
what you gotta do.

22:16.001 --> 22:18.037
Thank you, though.
Thank you so much.
Thank you so much, Sharks.

22:18.037 --> 22:20.206
Good luck, guys. Congrats.
Way to stick to your guns.

22:21.874 --> 22:23.843
We just weren't willing
to give up 1/3

22:23.843 --> 22:25.277
of what we've worked
so hard at,

22:25.277 --> 22:26.345
but at
the end of the day,

22:26.345 --> 22:28.047
we didn't feel like
his heart was in it.

22:28.047 --> 22:29.348
And that's
what we're in for,

22:29.348 --> 22:31.851
so, you know,
for that reason, we were out.

22:38.824 --> 22:41.660
Narrator: Next in the Tank
is a functional accessory

22:41.660 --> 22:43.662
for your furry pals.

22:46.832 --> 22:48.200
Aww.

22:52.671 --> 22:53.806
Hi, Sharks.

22:53.806 --> 22:55.307
I'm Shannon from
Austin, Texas,

22:55.307 --> 22:57.276
and this is my dog, Rishi.

22:57.276 --> 22:59.311
And I'm Griffin
from Oxnard, California,

22:59.311 --> 23:03.048
and we're seeking $400,000
for 6% equity in our company.

23:03.048 --> 23:04.450
Wow.

23:04.450 --> 23:07.353
More and more, our dogs
are going everywhere with us --

23:07.353 --> 23:09.688
in the car, on a hike,
to brunch,

23:09.688 --> 23:11.891
even on our
stand-up paddleboards.

23:11.891 --> 23:14.793
While our relationship with dogs
has completely modernized,

23:14.793 --> 23:17.363
most dog products are still
clunky, inconvenient,

23:17.363 --> 23:19.798
or something even your dog
would be embarrassed by.

23:19.798 --> 23:22.334
The most important thing
that your dog needs,

23:22.334 --> 23:24.303
besides pets and cuddles,
is water.

23:24.303 --> 23:25.771
But who here
has tried

23:25.771 --> 23:28.440
the "make your hand
into a bowl" method?

23:28.440 --> 23:31.443
It's messy, wastes water,
and doesn't work well.

23:31.443 --> 23:34.480
Or you can pour the contents
of your water bottle

23:34.480 --> 23:36.015
into a portable bowl...

23:36.015 --> 23:37.983
and when your dog
doesn't drink at all,

23:37.983 --> 23:39.785
you're left
having to throw it out.

23:40.886 --> 23:42.655
And public water bowls
can infect your pup

23:42.655 --> 23:44.223
with creepy bacteria.

23:44.223 --> 23:45.724
And let's be honest,

23:45.724 --> 23:48.327
we know you kiss
that mouth daily.

23:50.930 --> 23:53.299
So we invented
the Springer travel bottle,

23:53.299 --> 23:55.134
the best way
to give your dog water

23:55.134 --> 23:56.669
anywhere
at any time.

23:56.669 --> 23:57.836
Come here, bud.

23:57.836 --> 23:59.905
Simply squeeze
the bottle.

23:59.905 --> 24:02.007
The bowl will
fill up with water.

24:02.007 --> 24:03.609
When your dog
is done drinking,

24:03.609 --> 24:04.677
release the bottle,

24:04.677 --> 24:06.845
and the water
goes back into the bottle.

24:06.845 --> 24:09.348
No mess, no fuss,
and no wasting water.
Cuban: That's pretty cool.

24:09.348 --> 24:10.950
This is
just the first

24:10.950 --> 24:13.218
of many innovative products
in the pipeline

24:13.218 --> 24:15.454
that solve problems
that pet owners face every day.

24:15.454 --> 24:18.190
So, Sharks,
who's ready to join our pack

24:18.190 --> 24:21.660
and make Springer
top dog of the pet industry?

24:21.660 --> 24:23.662
It's really
a good idea.

24:23.662 --> 24:25.164
If it falls sideways,
does it leak?

24:25.164 --> 24:26.865
So there is
a leak-tight shut-off.

24:26.865 --> 24:28.067
We have to
tighten it?

24:28.067 --> 24:29.301
So you twist it
in the middle.

24:29.301 --> 24:30.502
Okay,
then it doesn't leak.

24:30.502 --> 24:32.204
Yes, and then it's
completely leak-tight.

24:32.204 --> 24:33.305
Greiner: Wow.

24:33.305 --> 24:34.673
Alright, so, listen,
tell us about you.

24:34.673 --> 24:36.008
How did you
come up with this?

24:36.008 --> 24:37.843
Our dad
is an inventor.

24:37.843 --> 24:40.012
He invented the first travel mug
35 years ago.

24:40.012 --> 24:41.313
Cuban: You guys
are brother and sister?

24:41.313 --> 24:42.448
Yes, my brother.

24:42.448 --> 24:44.683
So Griffin and I
actually started our careers

24:44.683 --> 24:47.319
as models
for the company.

24:47.319 --> 24:50.422
Oh, my God!
You're so cute.

24:50.422 --> 24:51.423
That's great.

24:51.423 --> 24:53.726
A few years ago,
I adopted Rishi.

24:53.726 --> 24:56.996
I became part of the demographic
of crazy dog parents

24:56.996 --> 24:58.731
that would do anything
for their dog

24:58.731 --> 25:00.866
but whose problems
weren't being addressed,

25:00.866 --> 25:02.401
and that's when
Springer was born.

25:02.401 --> 25:04.370
So what
am I investing in?
Springer.

25:04.370 --> 25:06.205
So we created
a new pet brand,

25:06.205 --> 25:08.107
Springer,
that sells this bottle.

25:08.107 --> 25:09.608
So this
is your first product.

25:09.608 --> 25:11.710
Yes.
Right?
Do you have any patents?

25:11.710 --> 25:14.313
Yes, we have eight patents
covering these products.

25:14.313 --> 25:15.581
Greiner: Eight?
Eight.

25:15.581 --> 25:17.016
Wow.

25:17.016 --> 25:19.485
Utility, design in the U. S.
and internationally.

25:19.485 --> 25:21.020
Cuban: So when did you start
going to market,

25:21.020 --> 25:22.287
and how
were you selling it?

25:22.287 --> 25:24.890
Our first year of sales
was in 2016,

25:24.890 --> 25:27.659
and we did about $711,000
in revenue in the first year.

25:27.659 --> 25:28.994
Wow.

25:28.994 --> 25:30.529
For the next
couple years,

25:30.529 --> 25:34.967
we sold between about $650,000
and $750,000 per year,

25:34.967 --> 25:37.903
and in 2020, we got
$1.7 million in sales.

25:37.903 --> 25:39.838
Wow.
And how much money
did you make?

25:39.838 --> 25:41.440
'Cause there's got to be
great margins.

25:41.440 --> 25:42.775
Yeah,
there are great margins.

25:42.775 --> 25:44.743
Yeah.
We made $100,000, and --

25:44.743 --> 25:45.911
That's not great.

25:45.911 --> 25:47.579
That's it?
$100,000?

25:47.579 --> 25:48.847
Yeah,
so last year,

25:48.847 --> 25:51.183
we decided it was gonna be
a growth year for us,

25:51.183 --> 25:53.385
so we reinvested
a lot of our profit

25:53.385 --> 25:55.387
into more IP, branding,

25:55.387 --> 25:58.090
building out new innovations
that are coming later this year.

25:58.090 --> 25:59.158
So tell us your margins.

25:59.158 --> 26:00.459
What does it cost
to make one of these?

26:00.459 --> 26:03.729
It is about $3 on average
to make one of these products.

26:03.729 --> 26:06.365
Our margins on retail
are 88%.

26:06.365 --> 26:09.701
Our mini --
the mini sells for $22,

26:09.701 --> 26:12.204
the medium size sells
for $25,

26:12.204 --> 26:13.705
and the growler
sells for $28.

26:13.705 --> 26:16.408
Those are great margins,
but where'd the money go?

26:16.408 --> 26:18.377
The $6.4 million valuation

26:18.377 --> 26:20.279
is a bit of a stretch
for a single-product company,

26:20.279 --> 26:22.481
but actually,
you're just breaking even.

26:22.481 --> 26:24.483
You're making $100,000
on $1.7 million.

26:24.483 --> 26:25.984
I'm calling that
breaking even.

26:25.984 --> 26:29.588
I'm looking for $500,000
worth of costs

26:29.588 --> 26:31.623
that I don't understand
where they are.

26:31.623 --> 26:34.026
Something is
eating up $500,000.

26:34.026 --> 26:35.694
You got
88% gross margins.

26:35.694 --> 26:37.229
Yeah, and something else
doesn't add up.

26:37.229 --> 26:39.932
We had a lot of investment in IP
and brand protection because --

26:39.932 --> 26:41.500
What was
the total expense of that?

26:41.500 --> 26:43.502
For branding,
it was about $150,000, website.

26:43.502 --> 26:44.837
Yeah, but you see how
all this doesn't add up,

26:44.837 --> 26:47.806
'cause those expenses
are accrued over five years.

26:47.806 --> 26:49.141
You know, so --
Well, a lot of it

26:49.141 --> 26:51.477
went invested
in the last year,

26:51.477 --> 26:53.412
and those are
one-time expenses.

26:53.412 --> 26:54.980
And then
we have a team,

26:54.980 --> 26:56.882
so it's us,
our parents.

26:56.882 --> 26:59.585
We have
two other employees in-house.

26:59.585 --> 27:01.019
What do you guys make?

27:01.019 --> 27:02.488
We make about $70,000.

27:02.488 --> 27:04.857
Look, I think the products
are really cool, right?

27:04.857 --> 27:06.558
They're ingenious
in a lot of respects,

27:06.558 --> 27:07.893
but what concerns me

27:07.893 --> 27:10.395
is that you've been
selling it for five years.

27:10.395 --> 27:12.197
I'm surprised
it hasn't done a lot more.

27:12.197 --> 27:14.533
For those reasons,
I'm out.

27:14.533 --> 27:16.902
Who is the person that came up
with the brilliant idea

27:16.902 --> 27:19.872
of only
offering us 6%?

27:19.872 --> 27:22.474
So to justify that,
we're on track this year

27:22.474 --> 27:24.143
to sell $2 million,

27:24.143 --> 27:28.480
and next year,
we're projected at $3.2 million.

27:28.480 --> 27:30.649
We can give you the money.
Is that all you want?

27:30.649 --> 27:31.850
We want
your expertise.

27:31.850 --> 27:33.685
We got to work, too,
for the money, right?

27:33.685 --> 27:36.555
For 6%? Really?
- What expertise do you need?

27:36.555 --> 27:38.223
John: Really?
You want me to pay

27:38.223 --> 27:41.326
and get a small return
and then work for you?

27:41.326 --> 27:44.029
It doesn't make
any sense to me.
We primarily --

27:44.029 --> 27:45.864
It's not worth my time.
I'm out.

27:45.864 --> 27:47.432
Okay.
Thank you.

27:47.432 --> 27:49.968
I think
it's a very good product,

27:49.968 --> 27:51.803
but I can't get past
one thing.

27:51.803 --> 27:54.540
And it might be
my own bias,

27:54.540 --> 27:56.542
and it might be my age.

27:56.542 --> 28:01.013
But the thing I was taught
is when you start a business,

28:01.013 --> 28:04.183
the first thing that gets paid
is the business.

28:04.183 --> 28:08.220
And the last thing
that gets paid is the owner.

28:08.220 --> 28:09.588
Yes,
and that's why the --

28:09.588 --> 28:11.223
And you're doing it
the opposite.

28:11.223 --> 28:13.725
You're paying yourself
$70,000 a year.

28:13.725 --> 28:16.929
I mean, you're starving
the business for cash

28:16.929 --> 28:18.597
to make a living.

28:18.597 --> 28:21.567
I don't want to be part of that.
I'm out.

28:21.567 --> 28:23.569
O'Leary: Okay, so let me
take a stab at this, alright?

28:23.569 --> 28:27.539
What I like about
this deal is sales.

28:27.539 --> 28:30.976
I love cash flow.
This is a family business.

28:30.976 --> 28:32.711
The only way
I would do this deal is

28:32.711 --> 28:35.047
I want to stay out of that soup,
alright?

28:35.047 --> 28:38.150
With a 6% ownership,
I have no say anyways.

28:38.150 --> 28:41.186
This is a royalty deal.
It keeps everything aligned.

28:41.186 --> 28:43.989
My interest to sell more
is very high,

28:43.989 --> 28:46.358
so I'll give you
the $400,000.

28:46.358 --> 28:47.826
I want 3% equity,

28:47.826 --> 28:50.829
as schmuck insurance,
in case the product gets sold

28:50.829 --> 28:52.998
while I'm in my royalty
agreement with you. Okay.

28:52.998 --> 28:55.500
And I want $3 a unit

28:55.500 --> 28:58.437
until I get my $400,000 back,

28:58.437 --> 29:01.473
and then I want half of that,
$1.50, in perpetuity.

29:01.473 --> 29:04.676
I have lots of people
can blow this up digitally,

29:04.676 --> 29:06.778
and I would do that 'cause
my interests are aligned.

29:06.778 --> 29:08.213
And that's my offer.

29:08.213 --> 29:09.214
Okay.
Okay. Thank you.
Yeah, thank you for your offer.

29:09.214 --> 29:10.215
We really appreciate
your offer.

29:10.215 --> 29:12.150
Thank you.
I love this.

29:12.150 --> 29:15.554
I think it is so smart
and so innovative,

29:15.554 --> 29:18.857
and just, like,
why would you use anything else?

29:18.857 --> 29:20.592
Yeah.
I'm gonna
make you an offer.

29:20.592 --> 29:24.896
I'm gonna give you
the 400K for 10%,

29:24.896 --> 29:27.899
but I want
preferred stock.

29:27.899 --> 29:31.770
Which means I would get
distributions first

29:31.770 --> 29:34.773
whenever there's profits
that are paid out.

29:34.773 --> 29:36.141
Awesome.
Okay.

29:36.141 --> 29:38.944
Thank you for your offer.
Would you do it for 8%?

29:38.944 --> 29:41.680
No, I got to stick at 10%,
you guys, come on.

29:41.680 --> 29:42.848
It's risky,

29:42.848 --> 29:46.118
and I got to be excited
to get out of bed.

29:53.959 --> 29:55.661
Lori, we'd be happy
to do that deal with you.

29:55.661 --> 29:56.928
- Yay!
- You got a deal!

29:59.097 --> 30:00.932
Yeah, Rishi!

30:00.932 --> 30:02.167
Fluffy, bite her.

30:02.167 --> 30:04.069
My first
inventor family!
Yay!

30:04.069 --> 30:05.203
Whoo!

30:07.139 --> 30:08.607
- We're so excited.
- So good.

30:08.607 --> 30:10.242
I'm so happy to be part
of the family.

30:10.242 --> 30:11.376
Bye, you.

30:11.376 --> 30:12.511
See you, guys. Congratulations.

30:12.511 --> 30:13.578
Well done.

30:13.578 --> 30:14.646
Enjoy those products, too.
Thank you.

30:14.646 --> 30:17.249
Whoo!

30:17.249 --> 30:18.950
Griffin: Now that we have Lori
on our team,

30:18.950 --> 30:20.452
we're ready
to blitz the market.

30:20.452 --> 30:21.887
She was
the ideal Shark for us.

30:21.887 --> 30:24.189
We feel like she's already part
of our Springer family.

30:24.189 --> 30:26.725
Whoo!
Whoo! Yes!

30:26.725 --> 30:28.160
Whoo!
We made a deal!

30:40.305 --> 30:42.174
Narrator:
Next up is a company

30:42.174 --> 30:45.210
that combines two loves
into one product.

30:55.253 --> 30:56.922
Hi, Sharks.
My name is Chase Terrell,

30:56.922 --> 30:58.557
and I'm from Sand Springs, Oklahoma.

30:58.557 --> 31:01.493
My name's Chris Diede,
and I live in Austin, Texas.

31:01.493 --> 31:03.662
This is my son
and my brother-in-law,

31:03.662 --> 31:05.897
and I'm Jake Rutledge,
the inventor of...

31:05.897 --> 31:08.600
Together:
The Chill-N-Reel!

31:08.600 --> 31:11.169
Today, we're fishing
for $300,000

31:11.169 --> 31:12.771
for a 10% stake
in our company.

31:12.771 --> 31:15.040
Wow.
My dad has solved

31:15.040 --> 31:17.809
one of the world's
<i>biggest</i> problems.

31:21.980 --> 31:25.016
Hold my beer!

31:26.485 --> 31:27.552
Chase,
hold my beer!

31:27.552 --> 31:28.587
I can't, man!

31:28.587 --> 31:29.821
My hands are full
over here, too!

31:29.821 --> 31:32.124
How am I supposed to
reel in this fish

31:32.124 --> 31:34.659
and hold my beer
at the same time?

31:36.361 --> 31:39.231
Together:
There's got to be a better way!

31:39.231 --> 31:41.900
That's why I invented
the Chill-N-Reel,

31:41.900 --> 31:44.302
the only drink insulator
you can fish with

31:44.302 --> 31:45.670
and the only
drink insulator

31:45.670 --> 31:47.606
with a hand-line reel
on the side.

31:47.606 --> 31:49.541
If you enjoy fishing,

31:49.541 --> 31:51.443
you know
how much of a hassle it is

31:51.443 --> 31:54.312
to pack all your gear
just to casually...

31:54.312 --> 31:55.580
pitch out a line.

31:59.151 --> 32:01.853
No way.
Obviously, the Chill-N-Reel
was not made

32:01.853 --> 32:03.321
to reel in a marlin.

32:03.321 --> 32:04.556
However,
what it <i>was</i> made for

32:04.556 --> 32:08.293
is nothing short
of a <i>real</i> good time.

32:08.293 --> 32:09.861
We have the Chill-N-Reel
designed to be

32:09.861 --> 32:13.031
easily cast-able, reel-able,
and, of course, drinkable.

32:13.031 --> 32:15.033
Just pitch it out,
grab your slack,

32:15.033 --> 32:17.636
and tip it back
and start reeling them in cold.

32:17.636 --> 32:21.006
We've caught bass, crappie,
and catfish on the Chill-N-Reel,

32:21.006 --> 32:23.442
but today,
we're fishing for Sharks.

32:23.442 --> 32:25.610
Together:
Who's gonna take a bite?

32:25.610 --> 32:26.745
Nice, nice.

32:26.745 --> 32:29.448
Where's the rod?
Like, how is the rod --

32:29.448 --> 32:30.649
That is the rod.

32:30.649 --> 32:31.950
Cuban:
There is no rod.
That's the rod?!

32:31.950 --> 32:33.685
All: This is it.

32:33.685 --> 32:35.654
Lori, with the fish you're
catching, this is good enough.

32:35.654 --> 32:38.156
So this just is basically
for smaller fish.

32:38.156 --> 32:39.491
You're not taking it
that serious, right?

32:39.491 --> 32:41.593
So how much pound test line
is on here?

32:41.593 --> 32:43.228
Eight-pound test
is on there.

32:43.228 --> 32:44.429
Eight pounds?

32:44.429 --> 32:47.599
Actually, I have thrown
50-pound braid on there,

32:47.599 --> 32:49.835
and I've caught
16-pound blue cat.

32:49.835 --> 32:52.604
I caught a 3 1/2-foot
hammerhead shark.

32:52.604 --> 32:54.139
Really?!
Yes.

32:54.139 --> 32:55.974
If you hold the line and try
to reel it, it'll cut your hand,

32:55.974 --> 32:59.511
but if you sit here
and use this as your crank --

32:59.511 --> 33:01.112
O'Leary:
Is that in Florida?
Yes.

33:01.112 --> 33:02.481
So tell us
what's happening there.

33:02.481 --> 33:04.683
Well, I'm reeling a fish in
right now.

33:04.683 --> 33:05.884
Where's the fish?

33:05.884 --> 33:07.986
He's coming.
He's coming.

33:07.986 --> 33:11.122
Boy, that's a big boy.
That's a big boy.

33:11.122 --> 33:12.190
Come on!

33:12.190 --> 33:14.159
Where's the shark?!

33:14.159 --> 33:15.760
I don't have my phone
or I'd pull it out and show you.

33:15.760 --> 33:16.761
Wah-wah.

33:16.761 --> 33:18.296
I hope they send it back,
right?

33:18.296 --> 33:19.598
Oh, yeah.

33:19.598 --> 33:21.299
Let's be clear, though,
this is not --

33:21.299 --> 33:22.734
it's not made
for the big guys.

33:22.734 --> 33:23.735
It's for those days

33:23.735 --> 33:25.270
when you just
want to chill and reel.

33:25.270 --> 33:26.972
It's fascinating.

33:26.972 --> 33:29.741
I got to know, what happened
to you guys to invent this?

33:29.741 --> 33:31.343
Okay,
here's the story.

33:31.343 --> 33:34.479
My family, we're on a family
vacation down in Florida,

33:34.479 --> 33:36.348
and we're all out
in the water drinking a beer.

33:36.348 --> 33:38.617
And I look down and
there's fish everywhere.

33:38.617 --> 33:42.020
Well, I got to catch those fish,
and my buddies looked at me.

33:42.020 --> 33:43.655
They said, "Man,
you bring a rod out here,

33:43.655 --> 33:45.824
you are gonna upset
everybody out here."

33:45.824 --> 33:47.359
I said, "Hey, watch this."

33:47.359 --> 33:48.960
I didn't even have to say,
"Hold my beer."

33:48.960 --> 33:52.631
I just went in, tied some line
onto the bottom of my koozie,

33:52.631 --> 33:53.999
wrapped it around,
would come out,

33:53.999 --> 33:55.300
pull all the string out,

33:55.300 --> 33:57.636
throw it out,
catch a fish, reel it in.

33:57.636 --> 33:59.704
I just kept spilling my beer everywhere.

33:59.704 --> 34:01.339
Did you catch anything?
Oh, yeah.

34:01.339 --> 34:02.807
We were always
catching fish.

34:02.807 --> 34:04.543
Jake,
what's your background?

34:04.543 --> 34:07.345
I've been a Tulsa firefighter
for 21 years.

34:07.345 --> 34:08.980
Good for you.
Thank you.

34:08.980 --> 34:13.485
So I have always wanted
to come up with something.

34:13.485 --> 34:15.153
And never
did you ever dream

34:15.153 --> 34:17.789
you'd be fishing
and drinking

34:17.789 --> 34:18.857
and ending up
on "Shark Tank."

34:18.857 --> 34:20.025
That's it.

34:20.025 --> 34:22.227
O'Leary: Why don't we start with
last year's sales

34:22.227 --> 34:24.262
and now what you're
gonna do this year?

34:24.262 --> 34:25.797
Well, I'll tell you,
the last 12 months,

34:25.797 --> 34:27.732
we've done
$1.34 million in sales.

34:27.732 --> 34:28.967
- What?
- You got to be kidding me?

34:28.967 --> 34:30.302
On this crap?

34:30.302 --> 34:31.836
This little thing.

34:31.836 --> 34:33.572
A lot of chill anglers
out there.

34:33.572 --> 34:35.373
Was not expecting
that answer.

34:35.373 --> 34:37.809
Yeah.
$1.3 million
in a year?

34:37.809 --> 34:39.210
That's right.
In the last 12 months.

34:39.210 --> 34:41.112
So last year,
up until June,

34:41.112 --> 34:43.148
there had been
$50,000 in sales,

34:43.148 --> 34:46.117
and then from then on, we
finished the year at $680,000.

34:46.117 --> 34:47.352
What about this year?

34:47.352 --> 34:49.287
This year, we're at
about $760,000 so far.

34:49.287 --> 34:51.556
Okay, and what do you think
you'll make this year?
So far.

34:51.556 --> 34:53.959
About $1.65 million.
Damn!

34:53.959 --> 34:56.995
So, guys, this thing is
a total little piece
of crap selling a ton.

34:58.029 --> 34:59.030
That's what I thought!

34:59.030 --> 35:00.565
I thought
the exact same thing

35:00.565 --> 35:01.666
until I saw this --

35:01.666 --> 35:03.668
that there was
this response that happened

35:03.668 --> 35:05.570
from people
who just want to be out,

35:05.570 --> 35:07.606
hang out on the water,
float the river.

35:07.606 --> 35:10.041
What does it cost to make,
and what do you sell one for?

35:10.041 --> 35:12.911
They sell for $12.95
for the solid colors,

35:12.911 --> 35:16.147
$15 for the camos.

35:16.147 --> 35:18.116
They cost us $2.06,

35:18.116 --> 35:21.653
and we manufacture
in Tulsa, Oklahoma.
All made in Oklahoma.

35:21.653 --> 35:22.921
Did you throw a lot of money
on marketing?

35:22.921 --> 35:24.155
We did. Okay.

35:24.155 --> 35:25.390
Yes.

35:25.390 --> 35:27.392
How much have you spent
in the last 12 months?

35:27.392 --> 35:28.693
Spent about 40%.

35:28.693 --> 35:30.061
So $400,000?

35:30.061 --> 35:31.363
Yes.
Little lower.

35:31.363 --> 35:33.098
Around $400,000.

35:33.098 --> 35:35.634
So -- Wow. So take out
the advertising cost.

35:35.634 --> 35:36.635
Yeah.

35:36.635 --> 35:39.270
What's your net margin?

35:39.270 --> 35:42.674
Last year, we made
a little over $70,000.

35:42.674 --> 35:44.309
And how much have you made
this year?

35:44.309 --> 35:47.112
This year,
we are negative $25,000.

35:47.112 --> 35:49.748
We just placed an order
for 54,000.

35:49.748 --> 35:51.182
So that's where
your cash went.

35:51.182 --> 35:52.250
Right.

35:52.250 --> 35:54.152
We've got $350,000
worth of inventory

35:54.152 --> 35:55.654
in our warehouse
right now.

35:55.654 --> 35:58.490
Look,
the thing is so ridiculous,

35:58.490 --> 36:01.493
but I can't help
but respect the sales.

36:01.493 --> 36:03.194
1.65 million bucks.

36:03.194 --> 36:05.397
I mean,
that's just --

36:05.397 --> 36:06.965
But it's such
a piece of crap.

36:07.966 --> 36:09.934
Look,
I wish you the best,

36:09.934 --> 36:11.302
but I can't invest
in this.

36:11.302 --> 36:12.637
I'm out.

36:12.637 --> 36:15.240
Oh, well, we hope
you'll reconsider.

36:16.474 --> 36:17.942
It's fun
for you guys.

36:17.942 --> 36:19.678
It's not investable
for me.

36:19.678 --> 36:22.113
It's not really a company
for me, you know?

36:22.113 --> 36:23.948
But I wish you
good luck.

36:23.948 --> 36:25.750
I love
what you've done.

36:25.750 --> 36:27.118
I'm out.

36:27.118 --> 36:28.119
Thank you, Lori.

36:28.119 --> 36:29.354
One thing I'd like to add, though,

36:29.354 --> 36:30.555
just so
you're all aware,

36:30.555 --> 36:32.957
we all think there's
some opportunities to license

36:32.957 --> 36:35.527
the technology, as well,
which happens to be patented.

36:35.527 --> 36:37.696
Reeling in on koozie?

36:37.696 --> 36:39.864
The drink insulator
that you can fish with.

36:39.864 --> 36:42.367
I want to be the patent officer
that saw that one.

36:43.735 --> 36:45.170
Daymond.

36:45.170 --> 36:47.872
What?
What are you gonna do?

36:47.872 --> 36:49.474
It's a great,
fun business.

36:49.474 --> 36:52.043
We're selling good times,
and people are buying.

36:52.043 --> 36:53.344
People are buying.
I don't want to ruin
your good time,

36:53.344 --> 36:55.780
but as an investor,
I'm not gonna have as much fun.

36:55.780 --> 36:57.415
Right?
I didn't come up with it.

36:57.415 --> 37:00.018
I'm not with you guys
every day running it.

37:00.018 --> 37:02.153
I just don't think it's for me,
so I'm out.

37:02.153 --> 37:04.322
Thank you.
I'm sorry to hear that.

37:04.322 --> 37:05.423
Herjavec: Mark?

37:05.423 --> 37:07.959
Look, guys, I've got
two fundamental problems.

37:07.959 --> 37:10.829
One, there's just not enough
net margin to it, right?

37:10.829 --> 37:12.997
You're spending 40%
on your advertising,

37:12.997 --> 37:14.365
and so that's really
where you've got

37:14.365 --> 37:15.834
to kind of
make it better.

37:15.834 --> 37:17.435
Right.
But even
if you did a lot better,

37:17.435 --> 37:20.772
there's not enough margin
left there for an investor,

37:20.772 --> 37:22.273
so that's
the first problem.

37:22.273 --> 37:25.577
But the bigger problem is,
as somebody who lives in Texas,

37:25.577 --> 37:27.879
if you can't hold your beer
no matter what,

37:27.879 --> 37:29.080
you're doing it wrong.

37:29.080 --> 37:30.415
So I'm out.

37:31.516 --> 37:34.119
Look,
I've been really thinking

37:34.119 --> 37:35.920
'cause first,
I was completely out,

37:35.920 --> 37:37.589
then I was
completely in,

37:37.589 --> 37:39.491
and one of you
said it --

37:39.491 --> 37:42.460
you're selling fun,
and people want fun.

37:42.460 --> 37:44.028
We just had
a year of COVID.

37:44.028 --> 37:45.697
We were all
locked up at home.

37:45.697 --> 37:48.266
People want excitement
and fun,

37:48.266 --> 37:49.701
and you're really
selling them,

37:49.701 --> 37:51.936
for a very small
price point,

37:51.936 --> 37:54.072
you're selling them fun.

37:54.072 --> 37:58.877
My issue is,
you know,

37:58.877 --> 38:01.613
there isn't enough room
in this deal.

38:01.613 --> 38:03.281
Like,
you guys are in a boat,

38:03.281 --> 38:06.117
and the boat
is staying afloat.

38:06.117 --> 38:08.186
but if I come in,
it's gonna sink.

38:08.186 --> 38:10.321
Or we're gonna get
a lot bigger of a boat.

38:10.321 --> 38:13.291
Gonna need a bigger boat.

38:13.291 --> 38:14.826
Diede: Where I think
we can really optimize

38:14.826 --> 38:17.395
on that margin with
the marketing and advertising

38:17.395 --> 38:19.697
is we've seen this year
as a branding year.

38:19.697 --> 38:21.166
That's what's been expensive,
I think,

38:21.166 --> 38:22.400
especially
this first year.

38:22.400 --> 38:23.868
That'll crunch in
as we get awareness.

38:23.868 --> 38:26.237
Chris, I've made
crazier investments

38:26.237 --> 38:28.006
and done really well.

38:28.006 --> 38:29.541
I just don't know.

38:29.541 --> 38:31.910
I mean,
I love the fun.

38:31.910 --> 38:34.145
I love the beer.

38:34.145 --> 38:36.014
This deal is
all about royalties.

38:36.014 --> 38:38.049
Oh!

38:49.661 --> 38:52.597
Narrator:
Four Sharks are out,

38:52.597 --> 38:55.366
and Robert is on the fence
about investing in Chill-N-Reel,

38:55.366 --> 38:57.836
a fishing reel
and beverage koozie.

38:57.836 --> 38:59.671
This deal is
all about royalties.

38:59.671 --> 39:01.139
Oh!

39:01.139 --> 39:03.808
What are you gonna do,
Robert?

39:04.976 --> 39:08.146
I will give you
the $300,000.

39:08.146 --> 39:12.951
I'll keep 10% as equity,
and I'll take $2...

39:12.951 --> 39:14.586
- Ooh.
- Ay, Chihuahua.

39:14.586 --> 39:16.287
...per reel.

39:16.287 --> 39:19.190
I like it. My first royalty
deal. This is exciting.

39:19.190 --> 39:21.159
Learn, grasshopper. Learn.

39:21.159 --> 39:23.561
What do you think?

39:23.561 --> 39:24.696
You have the margin
to do it.

39:24.696 --> 39:26.798
How long is the royalty
in place, Robert?

39:26.798 --> 39:29.167
As long as we're having
a good time, Daymond.

39:32.837 --> 39:35.840
So that's the difference
between Robert and Kevin.

39:35.840 --> 39:38.376
He said it very nicely,
but that means perpetuity.

39:39.777 --> 39:41.412
Cut the throat, man.

39:41.412 --> 39:42.914
You guys can counter.

39:42.914 --> 39:45.016
Uh...

39:45.016 --> 39:48.319
I don't think we're in
for royalties.

39:48.319 --> 39:49.621
Smart man.

39:49.621 --> 39:52.023
If you wanted
to go...

39:52.023 --> 39:55.126
15% for $300,000...

39:55.126 --> 39:56.728
we can do that.

39:56.728 --> 39:59.264
You don't like the royalty,
but you don't mind the equity.

39:59.264 --> 40:00.265
Right. Right.

40:00.265 --> 40:01.833
I mean, the money --

40:01.833 --> 40:04.903
Money's great,
but we're here for a partner.

40:04.903 --> 40:07.739
Alright.
$300,000. 35%.

40:07.739 --> 40:10.041
O'Leary: Ay, Chihuahua!

40:10.041 --> 40:12.176
It's not
a hard negotiation.

40:12.176 --> 40:13.845
I'm taking a flier
on you guys.

40:13.845 --> 40:16.247
I think you've really
figured out something.

40:16.247 --> 40:17.582
It may go somewhere.

40:17.582 --> 40:19.817
I'm willing to risk
the $300,000,

40:19.817 --> 40:23.154
and I've worked really hard
for $300,000.

40:23.154 --> 40:24.822
You know, people always
sit up here and they think,

40:24.822 --> 40:26.658
"Oh, it's just money
to you guys."

40:26.658 --> 40:29.460
I remember the days
where I worked my ass off

40:29.460 --> 40:32.997
for, you know, 10 bucks,
so it's a lot of money.

40:32.997 --> 40:34.499
I believe in you guys.

40:34.499 --> 40:36.868
That's my offer --
$300,000, 35%.

40:36.868 --> 40:38.303
You want to take it?

40:38.303 --> 40:40.471
I'm happy to go along
for the boat ride.

40:40.471 --> 40:42.373
If not, we'll have
a beer together.

40:42.373 --> 40:44.909
Would you go to 20%?

40:46.144 --> 40:47.512
No, no.

40:47.512 --> 40:48.880
Okay.

40:48.880 --> 40:53.084
I appreciate the offer,
but we're gonna have to decline.

40:53.084 --> 40:54.319
Way to
stick to your guns, guys.

40:54.319 --> 40:55.353
Thank you.
Good job.

40:55.353 --> 40:57.155
Cheers.
Thank you, guys.

40:57.155 --> 40:58.957
One, two, three.

41:01.159 --> 41:03.361
I have no idea
what we're saying, but drink.

41:03.361 --> 41:04.562
No idea.

41:04.562 --> 41:05.530
Thank you, guys.
Greiner:
Thank you, guys.

41:05.530 --> 41:06.597
Keep having fun
and making money.

41:06.597 --> 41:07.598
Appreciate it.
Thank you, guys.

41:07.598 --> 41:08.566
Good luck, guys.

41:09.867 --> 41:11.336
What were
they thinking?

41:11.336 --> 41:13.037
I don't know.

41:13.037 --> 41:14.205
That's surprised me.

41:14.205 --> 41:15.974
Everybody --
They thought it was fun.

41:15.974 --> 41:19.010
Everybody in the U. S.
is gonna think it was fun.

41:19.010 --> 41:20.411
We didn't catch
a Shark today,

41:20.411 --> 41:22.447
but hey, there's lots of sharks
out there.

41:22.447 --> 41:24.782
We'll go out
and catch one tomorrow...

41:24.782 --> 41:26.751
Together:
With the Chill-N-Reel.

41:26.751 --> 41:29.554
What a total piece of
and $1.6 million.

41:29.554 --> 41:30.755
Like, that's just --

41:30.755 --> 41:32.757
They were spending all that
money on advertising.

41:32.757 --> 41:33.758
That was the problem.

41:33.758 --> 41:35.293
That was a lot of money,
a lot.

41:35.293 --> 41:37.328
It was converting,
but it's a lot of money.

41:37.328 --> 41:38.830
Kevin,
I was so excited there.

41:38.830 --> 41:40.264
I thought I had a royalty deal
for a second.

41:40.264 --> 41:41.899
I wanted to know what it felt
like after all these years.

41:41.899 --> 41:44.469
If you'd gone to a buck a reel,
he would have done the deal.

41:44.469 --> 41:46.170
Buck a reel
gets the deal.
